    "title": "To do more with AI, you actually need to do less ‚Äî or, at least, furiously protect your attention.",
    "date": "2025-06-05",
    "content": "<p>To do more with AI, you actually need to do less ‚Äî or, at least, furiously protect your attention.</p>\n<p>Healthy constraints beget innovation (and force you to think creatively about how to use the tools to get something done where you might have otherwise called a meeting or hired someone).</p>\n<p>First step to AI mastery isn't buying an overpriced PDF of \"prompt templates\"; it's committing to:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Not typing (use dictation);</li>\n<li>Not taking meetings on Mondays (and, generally, not before noon);</li>\n<li>Not checking your email more than twice a day;</li>\n<li>Not ending a meeting without at least one very concrete, timebound commitment that wouldn't have been made otherwise;</li>\n<li>Not snacking on digital media (including and especially podcasts) for more than 10 minutes a day.</li>\n<li>Not negotiating input- or even output-based terms (outcomes only!);</li>\n<li>Not accepting anything less than excellence, from yourself and your collaborators;</li>\n<li>Cash up front with a satisfaction guarantee.</li>\n<li>Creating compelling facts and only then publishing the fruit of your work‚Äîversus \"storytelling\" and speculation (good results in private beget real insight in public; and</li>\n<li>Negotiating transcendent objectives‚Äîand concrete, time-bound measures of success‚Äîthat bind a cross-functional group, with Bayesian probability scoring along the way, before committing to an initiative.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>AI complements all of these healthy constraints; without them, it doesn't beget real transformation, of your own workflow or the organization writ large.</p>\n",
