    "date": "2025-05-27",
    "content": "<p>I've been spending a lot of quality time with the (proto) AI agents from the Labs: (i.e., <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a> Code, OpenAI Codex, Gemini Deep Research) and have come to the following conclusion:</p>\n<p>A lot software development, marketing, and discovery will be automated.</p>\n<p>But, not all of it.</p>\n<p>And it's those things that won't be (mostly as a function of \"shouldn't\" than \"can't\") where you'll be able to build meaningful market positions.</p>\n<p>That said, if you are not letting your people experiment‚Äîprudently‚Äîwith these frontier capabilities and then deducing the ways in which their roles and the emergent corporate structures around them will need to change, you are going to have a very painful wake up call sometime in the next 3‚Äì5 years, when a lean team comes out of nowhere and eats your lunch because they can handle the same scale and scope of market demand at 1/10th cost and moving 10x faster than you.</p>\n<p>This is a call-to-action for enterprise leaders, even in the most heavily regulated sectors: decentralize IT and build a culture of experimentation, ASAP, or you will come to regret it.</p>\n<p>I was extremely skeptical of the whole agent thing; I still am (about very specific claims being made), but am now seeing how computers that can not only crunch words, but also compose workflows on the fly, will lead to the emergence of a new type of company that will absolutely pose an existential threat to incumbents who enjoyed enviable market positions and proximity to capital in the 20th and early 21st centuries.</p>\n",
