    "id": "post-2025-05-25-7332376869163450369",
    "title": "However much you're talking to customers, I can basically guarantee it less than the optimal amount.",
    "date": "2025-05-25",
    "content": "<p>However much you're talking to customers, I can basically guarantee it less than the optimal amount.</p>\n<p>[and this actually matters more, not less, in the context of ubiquitous ai, which can help you get some, but not all, and likely not the most important info you need when going 0‚Äì1 or 1‚Äì10...]</p>\n<p>There was a Y Combinator clip going around (but I can't seem to find...) where the partners were talking about how \"because of AI you don't actually need to do discovery interviews with users and you can just build stuff and see if the market reacts.</p>\n<p>This is sort of technically correct, but so deeply thematically wrong that it almost feels like a psyop on the competition.</p>\n<p>There is information in people's heads that doesn't show up anywhere in their digital exhaust and‚Äîwhile the AI voice assistants, which I love, are getting better and better at eliciting some of that subjective info, which is absolutely critical to figuring out what really is the essence of your product because latent within answers to counterfactual questions, invitations to tell stories, probing follow ups to emotional responses, etc is not just the immanent know-that and know-how you can bake into a database or code, but also the know-why of their intentions and the know-who in their undocumented networks of trust‚ÄîI have an extremely strong hunch that the best insights can only emerge through live interpersonal interaction (telling and showing and, now, co-creating), complemented but never substituted by AI-ified media.</p>\n<p>Sure, ship that cool prototype and pay attention to the results‚ÄîBUT, make sure you set aside ~$30k and cofounder hours to get to 25‚Äì50 deep discovery interviews each planning cycle (around eg a new ICP, major change in strategy, and so on).</p>\n<p>These are NOT sales discovery interviews.</p>\n<p>You are purely there to learn and be curious; don't say a word about you or your product unless they beg you to at the end. Ask questions, ensure they're doing most of the talking, and set the bar at deriving one surprising actionable insight per conversation (doesn't count otherwise). At 50 of these in 2‚Äì3 weeks, and you will know these people inside and out (if you do a good job, which necessitates a tiny bit of prep but mostly an attentive, curious, and charitable disposition).</p>\n<p>Happy to share more concrete tips, just dm me ..</p>\n",
