    "content": "<p>AI Literacy: The New Legal Competitive Edge</p>\n<p>47% of executives are increasing AI literacy budgets this year. Meanwhile, most law firms are still debating whether AI matters.</p>\n<p>The data is clear: 84% of business leaders now consider AI literacy a priority - and they expect their legal advisors to keep pace.</p>\n<p>What separates leading legal teams:</p>\n<p>‚û¢ They understand AI capabilities AND limitations</p>\n<p>‚û¢ They provide nuanced guidance beyond \"be careful with AI</p>\n<p>‚û¢ They integrate AI knowledge into strategic advice</p>\n<p>‚û¢ They're winning clients specifically because of this expertise</p>\n<p>As one GC recently shared: \"We switched outside counsel because our new firm could have intelligent conversations about AI use cases. The old firm couldn't move beyond generic warnings.</p>\n<p>üîë The bottom line: AI literacy isn't optional tech knowledge - it's becoming a fundamental business skill for legal professionals who want to remain valuable strategic advisors.</p>\n<p>True competitive advantage doesn't come from simply using AI tools, but from deeply understanding how they transform the practice of law.</p>\n<p>#LegalInnovation #AIForLawyers #LegalTech</p>\n",
