    "id": "post-2025-05-14-7328416283903881216",
    "title": "In an AI-native organization, everyone:",
    "date": "2025-05-14",
    "content": "<p>In an AI-native organization, everyone:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>submits PRs;</li>\n<li>expects meetings to be of the utmost quality;</li>\n<li>takes action, with great conviction, under conditions of uncertainty;</li>\n<li>activates the growth engine by, eg, energizing their network with free insights derived from the good work they do in private;</li>\n<li>understands that tending a 21st c. product portfolio is more like cultivating a garden than assembling strips of one-size-fits-all brutalist buildings;</li>\n<li>contributes to a larger goal in a way that is, by default, fractional, asynchronous, remote, and results-based;</li>\n<li>carefully guards his or her attention; deep work once a week as an absolute baseline;</li>\n<li>wills the good of the customer, always;</li>\n<li>carefully curated context, for tasks delegated to AI systems AND complex problems that necessitate \"multi-agent\" human reasoning (Orsen Welles‚Äìstyle \"situation architecture\" will likely be a core skill for generating novel options; a borderline‚Äìdogmatic and Bayesian approach to singular but rigorously defined goal pursuit that gets at the essence of the problem is complementary); and</li>\n<li>never forgets that reality is the best medium.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There are myriad ways to achieve this: a Cambrian explosion of tools, new problem frontiers that were previously intractable and now invite capital, and so on ‚Äî but it is entirely up to you to figure out how to get there, and that necessitates action and experimentation, TODAY!</p>\n",
