    "title": "I can say confidently that there are plenty of tasks across growth, operations, and product development that can be accomplished 10x faster with AI support/workflow integration ‚Äî software development being a prime example, especially recently thanks to nascent agents like Claude Code ‚Äî and yet.",
    "date": "2025-04-07",
    "content": "<p>I can say confidently that there are plenty of tasks across growth, operations, and product development that can be accomplished 10x faster with AI support/workflow integration ‚Äî software development being a prime example, especially recently thanks to nascent agents like <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a> Code ‚Äî and yet...</p>\n<p>I know that, in practice, most enterprises ‚Äî even the ones led by forward-thinking executives ‚Äî aren't getting the benefits.</p>\n<p>How could I know this?</p>\n<p>Well, most employees are simply not allowed to use the exact tools they need to achieve those outsized productivity boosts (and for understandable reasons: legacy IT processes, concerns about compliance, and so on).</p>\n<p>This raises some really interesting questions in re how an enterprise can sustain its market power when core parts of its value chain operate 5-10x slower than what's SOTA (and it's not clear that the frontier / best practice gap is going to close any time soon):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>is there some qualitative dark matter inside of an enterprise (eg., sticky culture, trust, tacit knowledge) that's not well accounted for and contributes to a sustained market position? Yes, and...</li>\n<li>are switching costs significantly higher than anyone thinks (in opaque forms w/ complex decision-making processes and occulted political structures, the answer is almost certainly yes)?</li>\n<li>will these positions continue to be durable as we live through unprecedented macro changes?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In practice, beyond the organizational context, I've found a few traits that seem to be highly correlated with ability to benefit from AI:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>openness as in OCEAN (not surprising),</li>\n<li>expertise (10y experience is just about right, because you know what \"good\" looks like), and</li>\n<li>focus on outcomes over precise process adherence; the people who struggle the most IME cannot help but get fixated on the deviations from the details of a process they associate with their own mastery of an art (and possibly sense of professional self) ‚Äî the antidote is to prioritize customer good or, proximally, the outcome that most effects it, and then furiously experiment until you've compressed some slice of a cycle.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you want to set up your team for success ‚Äî whether you're leading an SMB, VC-backed startup, or multibillion-dollar enterprise ‚Äî you can absolutely take right-sized steps in a good direction.</p>\n<p>It all starts with finding that one person in your organization who has the traits and temperament I described above, arming them (in a safe way) with the most powerful general tools you can, and pairing them with an expert (üëã) who can coach them through a handful of quick wins that \"create compelling facts\" and organically attract the attention and interest of more conservative peers.</p>\n<p>No better time than today (literally) to get started ‚Äî the long-term good of your investors, employees, and (most importantly) customers may depend on it.</p>\n",
