    "title": "I've served well over 100 clients since starting my consultancy about three years ago and had a very odd realization this morning.",
    "date": "2025-03-26",
    "content": "<p>I've served well over 100 clients since starting my consultancy about three years ago and had a very odd realization this morning.</p>\n<p>Of all of my engagements, I'd say there are only four that didn't go particularly well (really three clients and one prospect), and I was trying to think to myself, \"what were the common denominators?</p>\n<p>Literally, the one thing that was common across all of them was that the employees refused to turn their cameras on during Zoom meetings.</p>\n<p>Not sure what to make of it, but this was literally the one thing that was the same across all of them ‚Äî not the industry, department, geo, or anything else.</p>\n<p>Just that they would not show their faces on video calls.</p>\n<p>Not sure what to make of this.</p>\n<p>(Though I do have newfound sympathy/empathy for CPOs/CHROs who were particularly scrupulous about reminding colleagues of the \"camera on\" remote meeting policy at the beginning of the pandemic üòÇ)</p>\n",
