    "id": "post-2025-01-15-7285329516271411200",
    "title": "When I was at MIT Sloan, I was fortunate to take a class taught by Professor Eric Von Hippel.",
    "date": "2025-01-15",
    "content": "<p>When I was at MIT Sloan, I was fortunate to take a class taught by Professor Eric Von Hippel. In this class, I learned about user-led innovation, the sticky information problem, and several other deeply insightful concepts from his research and work. These concepts profoundly changed the way I think about product development, entrepreneurship, and the practical application of general-purpose technology, like generative AI.</p>\n<p>Whenever I'm surprised by the creative ways users of the products have contributed to developments during feedback and discovery interviews, I feel energized. This happened last night when I caught up with one of my private alpha participants. He figured out a clever solution to a dilemma he faced. On one extreme, he had zero insight into meetings he didn't attend, and on the other, he was attending every meeting. The solution was to have employees use their Fireflies note-taker to join meetings. He could then find out important details through his daily pulse message and communicate with Spark, his AI chief of staff.</p>\n<p>However, there was another category he hadn't considered: meetings he might want to attend or get more visibility into immediately after, without being present for the entire duration. He realized he could send his Fireflies note-taker and give other attendees a heads up. This would trigger my product to send notes at the meeting level rather than waiting for all aggregation the next day.</p>\n<p>This brilliant little innovation is something I'm excited to share with my other customers. It's another unexpected insight I'm gaining as I work with clients to apply AI, which is primarily a social technology, for more efficient information sharing and ultimately accelerating growth.</p>\n",
