    "id": "post-2024-12-30-7279534874309398528",
    "title": "It's been almost a month since I shelled out $200 for the new, higher ChatGPT tier.",
    "date": "2024-12-30",
    "content": "<p>It's been almost a month since I shelled out $200 for the new, higher <a href=\"https://chat.openai.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ChatGPT</a> tier.</p>\n<p>With frequent, daily use, it's clear: <a href=\"https://o1.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">o1 Pro</a> is overpowered; it's smarter than I am.</p>\n<p>I used to be able to get away with skimming SOTA model responses and muddling through to the next task.</p>\n<p>Now, I have to read the responses carefully, chew on the content, consider that it might have come to better conclusions in areas I'd considered myself an expert.</p>\n<p>The prose is dense. It's thoughtful. I sense that it's telling me things that are true that I may not want to hear‚Äîsometime obliquely, as if it anticipates some defensiveness.</p>\n<p>The bottleneck is my own context window, then: the rate at which I can take the right action to generate more data to pop back into the exchange (thoughts via dictation, console output while testing code changes, the transcript of a voice assistant conversation with a third-party from whom I need more information).</p>\n<p>Means that knowing where to point the coin-operated computer will be of greater importance‚Äîgood goals, ordered desire, \"taste.</p>\n<p>I'm seeing sparks of ASI.</p>\n",
