    "date": "2024-12-07",
    "content": "<p>Had assumed \"AI agents\" would be some invisible internet-native swarm intelligence type thing with predefined function calling as opposable thumbs into APIs, but...</p>\n<p>Maybe the actual general purpose \"agent\" is an old MacBook with a new login + eg <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a> Computer Use, OAI Operator and accounts controlled by you?</p>\n<p>Easy way to meet people (and corporations) where they already are ‚Äî onboarding a new \"employee\" is as easy as setting them up with a few seat-based licenses, screen recording software for troubleshooting/auditing, and giving them some direction (even setting up daily, then weekly lol, 1:1s as the models get better, context windows get longer, etc.).</p>\n<p>Things will get weird when, suddenly, the</p>\n<ol>\n<li>cost (not just in $ but also your attention as a manager) and</li>\n<li>achievable business outcomes of a Mac Mini and 24/7 AI API calls</li>\n</ol>\n<p>is at parity with an FTE recent Master's grad.</p>\n<p>(We are, of course, already far beyond that point for particular slices of a given workflow, which is why enterprise SaaS exists; ~full, general substitution would be a qualitative shift, which is I suppose what people mean when they talk about AGI.)</p>\n<p>That said, less talk and more action: I'm going to go install Computer Use on an old laptop, give it direction in re prospecting research, and let it run wild for as long as I can.</p>\n<p>Will report back on results + ROI, if any*...</p>\n<ul>\n<li>I continue to expect that what I described is maybe a little less than a decade away because of the reliability issue (compounding errors are expensive, either because they lead to worse results OR the test-time compute necessary to mitigate them may exceed the value until we reach some $/FLOP threshold.</li>\n</ul>\n",
