    "id": "post-2024-09-27-7245417500224495617",
    "title": "The artisanal software Cambrian explosion is coming.",
    "date": "2024-09-27",
    "content": "<p>The artisanal software Cambrian explosion is coming.</p>\n<p>There's going to be some small % of non-SWEs (maybe you!) who:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>get swept up in these o1 / Sonnet 3.5 / Cursor / Replit hype waves,</li>\n<li>stay focused and make it all the way through their first deployment,</li>\n<li>have a deep enough understanding of an esoteric problem space that it's pretty easy for them to work against an implicit product roadmap, and then</li>\n<li>keep the blinders on through a few deep work cycles per week, rapidly iterating until they have something that's, like, a full-fledged product (!) that</li>\n<li>catches fire within the high-trust/high-quality network to which they have privileged access.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I'll say from experience, once you go 0 to 1 doing this kind of thing (at least, at each incremental step), it'll be a lot easier to go 1 to n ‚Äî and turning your thoughts into code that just...WORKS...is a special kind of thrill that doesn't really exist in other white collar workflows.</p>\n<p>I imagine we'll see some really interesting team structures and corporate norms emerge to support this kind of thing, and that's something I'll continue to pay close attention to ‚Äî IMO AI-as-information-technology-per-se is significantly less than interesting than the social technology it enables...</p>\n<p>Stay tuned!</p>\n",
