    "id": "post-2024-09-19-7242562562528088064",
    "title": "I've been trying to think through what exactly constitutes a \"data asset,\" the economic complement to AI your business continuously generates, cultivates, and capitalizes upon.",
    "date": "2024-09-19",
    "content": "<p>I've been trying to think through what exactly constitutes a \"data asset,\" the economic complement to AI your business continuously generates, cultivates, and capitalizes upon...</p>\n<p>And after doing some noodling this morning, it occurred to me that \"cornered resources\" (in the Hamilton Helmer 7 Powers sense) have roughly the following schema in the AI age ‚Äî they can be digitized and indexed in such a way that they're made more useful as the foundation models become more capable:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>rare records (\"know-that,\" especially that which obviates limiting beliefs and unlocks opportunities to obliterate, rather than simply automate, existing processes),</li>\n<li>novel methods (\"know-how,\" which can be increasingly encoded in software as tacit knowledge becomes legible to multimodal models that can \"unstick\" information from raw process recordings), and</li>\n<li>trust (\"know-who,\" which is at least a model of the formal interpersonal structure within a larger organization, and, at best, meaningful relationships with those same folks)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now, how this gets captured, modeled, and mined is an entirely different question, and one I'll be continuing to investigate ‚Äî although I have some strong early indications that the way this worked in the past (e.g., via relational databases and traditional CRMs) will be very different than what the \"AI-native\" architecture looks like going forward ... more to come :)</p>\n<p>[this is just 1 of 5 takeaways (each w/ an actionable insight) from my great \"private podcast\" convo w/ Stewart Alsop this am ‚Äî we do these bi-monthly, and they've been indispensable as I've tried to continue making sense of what I'm encountering helping clients apply AI to solve their problems faster + integrate the tech into org's at lots of different levels of size & scope...]</p>\n<p>He's a great interviewer!</p>\n<p>Would highly recommend dm'ing Stewart if you could use some help periodically updating your / your business's longer-term view w/ a helpful thought partner...</p>\n",
    "excerpt": "I've been trying to think through what exactly constitutes a \"data asset,\" the economic complement to AI your business continuously generates, cultivates, and...",
    "type": "post",
    "originalUrl": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn%3Ali%3Ashare%3A7242562562528088064"
