    "id": "post-2024-08-20-7231771562054463489",
    "title": "Some good insights in this latest piece on enterprise AI from McKinsey & Company, BUT there's something missing.",
    "date": "2024-08-20",
    "content": "<p>Some good insights in this latest piece on enterprise AI from McKinsey & Company, BUT there's something missing...</p>\n<p>While, yes, you should:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>make it easy for employees to tinker with the tech and achieve quick wins,</li>\n<li>invest (quite a bit) in user-centric evangelism and change management, and</li>\n<li>take a longer-term \"don't automate; obliterate\" BPR view on how the technology should be used to reform the internals of your organization...</li>\n</ul>\n<p>...all that will still not be quite enough to yield the transformational results this once-in-a-century general purpose technology can be used to produce when wielded by visionary private and public sector leaders.</p>\n<p>You ALSO:</p>\n<p>Need to set ambitious goals that unify cross-functional teams‚Äîthese ambitious goals (i.e., extraordinary & measurable outcomes oriented around willing the good of your customer) serve as invitations for every single employee to strive to do new things with AI on an ongoing basis: not just \"1 to n\" continuous improvement, but \"0 to 1\" continuous innovation at speeds that are only possible because we all now have this incredible capability to delegate reading, writing, and even thinking tasks to word-crunching machines.</p>\n<p>Top-down provision of AI tools to everyone in the organization is a great start; bottoms-up, user-led innovation is a great next step.</p>\n<p>But, it's ultimately inside-out orientation of the organization's collective attention on a unifying goal that gets you to the radical transformation you've been promised.</p>\n<p>Now, set some bold goals and figure out how use AI to get there 10x faster!</p>\n",
