    "id": "post-2024-08-11-7228501905952428033",
    "title": "One thing I know to be true that few other AI bulls would agree with me on (even people at Labs tbh) is that \"prompt engineering\" as it's commonly understood is not a real thing‚Äîand never has been.",
    "date": "2024-08-11",
    "content": "<p>One thing I know to be true that few other AI bulls would agree with me on (even people at Labs tbh) is that \"prompt engineering\" as it's commonly understood is not a real thing‚Äîand never has been.</p>\n<p>Long detailed prompts are a waste of time unless they were constructed by a top 1% expert for the particular task (they implicitly know what part of the model to sample, which is best derived from live Q&A, not typing) and contain a whole bunch of gold standard outputs (and, at best, the exact inputs from which they were derived).</p>\n<p>If you want to get good at this stuff, spend less time messing around with xml tags and more time rapidly experimenting in a pocket of reality that's outside of the training data and record the process + results (only then, stuff all the good stuff into the context window).</p>\n",
    "excerpt": "One thing I know to be true that few other AI bulls would agree with me on (even people at Labs tbh) is that \"prompt engineering\" as it's commonly understood...",
