    "id": "post-2024-08-01-7224765037398106113",
    "title": "One of my favorite AI tools is Loom.",
    "date": "2024-08-01",
    "content": "<p>One of my favorite AI tools is Loom.</p>\n<p>Now, I love Loom because it's not a pure AI tool, let's say like <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a> or <a href=\"https://chat.openai.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ChatGPT</a>, but it quickly becomes an essential part of the toolkit if you're going operate your business in an AI-native way.</p>\n<p>This means, when it comes to team norms and managerial capacity, you need to be able to work with other folks remotely (and then probably asynchronously and even in a fractional capacity).</p>\n<p>This involves partnering with talented people for one-off deliverables or more expert indie consultants on high-stakes big upside outcomes for clients or customers. Traditionally, this would be prohibitively expensive because of search, onboarding, and switching costs.</p>\n<p>TBH, I used to actually really dislike Loom (which basically records your screen and allows you to provide a voiceover and bundles it into a video message URL you can send) because it puts a huge burden on the recipient to watch a long-form video, which consumes a lot of time and attention just to get the core content.</p>\n<p>But, thanks to AI, it's now really easy to take the transcript of Loom video, pop it into a tool like <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a>, and then quickly get what you need.</p>\n<p>This is a highly recommended habit for high-performing AI native teams.</p>\n<p>The Loom + <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a> combo allows you to capture, communicate, and consume information significantly more efficiently while also giving people the freedom to do work when and how they want.</p>\n<p>This also has the nice benefit of passively cultivating a data asset that you can use to grow your business and make training new employees or onboarding contractors ten times as fast.</p>\n<p>Tacit knowledge that would otherwise get lost is now on-the-record and retrievable!</p>\n<p>Loom has this great new feature where you can one-click create an SOP based on the video, which is something I've been recommending to clients.</p>\n<p>It is a different way of working though and necessitates the cultivation of new habits.</p>\n<p>The very first step I would recommend to get going in the right direction is to choose a particular task where you have to do something repetitive, time box it to let's say 50 minutes, and then before you dive in hit the record button on Loom.</p>\n<p>At that point I found it's actually easier to focus because you have this feeling that somebody's watching you and if things go right they will watch you in the future because this video will enter your internal knowledge base or be communicated elsewhere.</p>\n<p>And then, too, if you accomplish the task and even get a few reps in by the end, you can turn that into a nugget of valuable know-how immediately available to be posted in your company knowledge base (or, short of something highly structured, just a open Slack channel that anybody can search when they come on board).</p>\n<p>Do you use Loom at work? Let me know in the comments.</p>\n",
