    "id": "post-2024-06-18-7208839903143415808",
    "title": "Every week, I practice what I preach and try to accelerate my consultancy's progress towards my highest-order goals with an AI-assisted OKR sync.",
    "date": "2024-06-18",
    "content": "<p>Every week, I practice what I preach and try to accelerate my consultancy's progress towards my highest-order goals with an AI-assisted OKR sync.</p>\n<p>Here are a few things I learned this week:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Digital tools for not just remote but asynchronous communication and collaboration are getting better and better. I really believe if you're able to put constraints in place that force you to learn how to use them to solve problems for other people, it ends up being a major advantage because you're afforded many more degrees of freedom.</li>\n<li>For example, instead of automatically scheduling a call, I try to do as much discovery as I can upfront using AI tools to do deep research on a client or prospect, codify my analysis in a Figma  whiteboard, and then send a rich and comprehensive Loom  video with a call to action to take the next step. This could be scheduling a live call, talking to a voice agent who can ask the person specific questions, or even paying via a Stripe custom product link for a particular output or outcome that I propose. This has allowed me to align the hardest problems with the times of the day when my energy levels are highest.</li>\n<li>I'm continually surprised and fascinated by this liminal space between people and computers when it comes to delegation. As AI becomes more capable, hiring computers for a particular task rather than a person becomes a lot more sensible (eg MultiOn for information retrieval vs. or prior to hiring a freelance researcher.) However, there are cases where pure human labor is more reliable. This necessitates discernment when it comes to the what/when/how of \"who\" to delegate to, whether it's speed, quality, reliability, the amount of information that you're at liberty to share, etc.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I'll continue to report back on what I learned but the bottom line is AI-powered humans that are distributed in space and time are a whole new category of workforce that I expect to emerge in interesting ways in the years ahead.</p>\n<p>Feel free to add questions in the comments.</p>\n<p>(I'll probably start publishing these updates on a more regular basis as I figure out what exactly it takes to ride the AI wave and build a business in a new way that the technology fundamentally enables.)</p>\n",
    "excerpt": "Every week, I practice what I preach and try to accelerate my consultancy's progress towards my highest-order goals with an AI-assisted OKR sync. Here are a...",
    "type": "post",
    "originalUrl": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn%3Ali%3AugcPost%3A7208839903143415808"
