    "id": "post-2024-05-29-7201557096595697666",
    "title": "Interesting study.",
    "date": "2024-05-29",
    "content": "<p>Interesting study.</p>\n<p>I have three comments, based on my professional experience integrating Generative AI into production workflows from the level of the sole proprietorship all the way up to the enterprise over the past year+:</p>\n<p>First, even within the same function, I've observed consistently a power law distribution in terms of technology usage and value created. As a rule of thumb, one person amongst a peer group of 10 colleagues with similar responsibilities will account for 90% of the usage and also a similar percentage of value created. Most of that value is in cycle time reduction, which allows them to invest surplus time and attention into higher order activities that you couldn't have necessarily anticipated. While yes, you can make those user-led innovation‚Äìdriven workflows powered by AI more accessible to their peers with streamlined user experiences and some custom software development, from what I can tell, the power law curve still applies, and I'd even go so far to speculate that in general the ceiling is rising faster than the floor. (The glib version of this comment would be, \"skill issue,\" although it's probably more accurate to describe the limiting factors as \"mindset\" and \"desire\" more specifically.)</p>\n<p>Applying this in aggregate, it's entirely possible that we might, at least in certain sectors, only see a marginal bump in GDP. However, at the levels of specific individuals and businesses, the differences could be quite extreme.</p>\n<p>Second, information technology and the internet in general dovetail with generative AI and so lower barriers to global labor market participation in ways beyond just space - including time, culture, language, and many other dynamics one might consider. This is likely to put downward pressure on white-collar wages in developed countries for existing, known tasks, especially since young, very online, AI powered autodidacts in, say, Subharan Africa, are more flexible on important things like \"business model,\" e.g., outcome-based compensation and fractional employment as the norm vs. the FTE expectation in the US.</p>\n<p>Third, the new jobs, unmet needs, problems, and capital configurations that will likely emerge as the technology becomes more capable and integrated into the broader global economy are not just unknown, but probably unknowable and even unimaginable.</p>\n<p>As individuals reclaim surplus time, attention, and energy, they'll discover new, compelling, and unexpected ways to utilize it, unlocking new economic opportunities, generating insights about our world, and broadening our access to both information space and reality itself.</p>\n<p>Although I am a fan of AI mythbusting (there is much hype that needs to be dispelled), I'm largely optimistic that everyone will have the opportunity to experience significant benefits. However, it's important to acknowledge that it's impossible to know, or even really speculate, how exactly this might unfold until the experiment has been conducted.</p>\n",
