    "id": "post-2024-02-07-7161060165788585984",
    "title": "Building a company is like crossing a foggy river.",
    "date": "2024-02-07",
    "content": "<p>Building a company is like crossing a foggy river.</p>\n<p>The \"foggy river\" metaphor is a mental model I like to share with executive teams at the beginning of a new OKR (objective & key results) engagement.</p>\n<p>Recently, I shared this‚Äîand a few related ideas‚Äîwith a new client before we dove into a 6-hour objective-setting exercise.</p>\n<p>Before setting organization-wide goals, I think it's important to understand the purpose of those goals, and how we can think about goal-setting under conditions of incomplete information.</p>\n<p>Here's some of what we covered:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Managing uncertainty: the future is unknowable, so run experiments and disperse the fog</li>\n<li>Companies as unified organisms, cells working together towards shared goals</li>\n<li>Stepping stones vs. long-term plans: be agile and adapt along the way</li>\n<li>Learning over progress: insights and information edge drive value creation</li>\n<li>Quarterly cadence: breakthrough often comes at the 2nd/3rd month mark</li>\n<li>Alignment = collective flow state. Misalignment = teams pulling apart</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Check out the attached video for more details.</p>\n",
