    "id": "post-2024-02-05-7160297533292847104",
    "title": "A simple way to think about what‚Äôs going on with AI is that really the scope of what can be computed is growing.",
    "date": "2024-02-05",
    "content": "<p>A simple way to think about what‚Äôs going on with AI is that really the scope of what can be computed is growing.</p>\n<p>More dimensions of reality can be made legible to machines and then processed in a useful way.</p>\n<p>Computers used to only be able to crunch numbers, now they can crunch words.</p>\n<p>Soon, images, video, raw audio, and more esoteric modalities.</p>\n<p>In my enthusiastic, but somewhat tempered view, this means that on net, we‚Äôll probably get something like 50% of our time back.</p>\n<p>This is neither the Terminator-like apocalypse nor transhumanist utopia that seem to attract so much attention.</p>\n<p>I generally expect that because it turns out so much of what humans do actually requires high degrees of reliability in between tasks, it‚Äôll take a good 8 to 10 years for the scope of what‚Äôs computable to actually expand enough that AI becomes ubiquitous like electricity.</p>\n<p>But even prior to that, I do think that there‚Äôs one practical and still kind of philosophical question worth contemplating, which is, if you do end up getting 50% of your time back, what exactly are you going to spend it on?</p>\n<p>Are you going to treat it like an investment good or a consumption good?</p>\n<p>Broadly speaking, I think there are four buckets of activity that both complement what‚Äôs possible with AI, and also make sense as far as where to consider investing your attention, depending on your goals, your environment, and your personal temperament.</p>\n<p>Those are creation, relation, contemplation, and orchestration.</p>\n<p>There‚Äôs a positive version of each, but then there‚Äôs a negative version, where each go out of balance, detailed in the image below.</p>\n",
