    "title": "Great article.",
    "date": "2023-12-14",
    "content": "<p>Great article. I'm curious about how this changes the nature of what marketing executives (and their teams) do on a daily basis.</p>\n<p>If AI systems can be expected to more efficiently gather, analyze, and synthesize insights from digital exhaust AND generate/serve the content accordingly, then what exactly is left for CMOs to do?</p>\n<p>(I have a hunch, but as someone who is not a CMO, I'd like to leave it as an open question...)</p>\n<p>The Meta + Google ads products are rapidly becoming vertically integrated, commoditizing if not outright subsidizing a lot of what marketing ops folks have been doing for the past two decades, and the fight for consumer attention is brutally competitive (and more difficult for advertisers, e.g., due to nominally privacy-preserving design decisions by Apple).</p>\n<p>If we extrapolate 3‚Äì5 years in the future, and more of these tasks are delegated to machines, where exactly could we expect top CMOs invest their surplus attention?</p>\n",
