    "id": "post-2023-10-16-7119750106307776512",
    "title": "Many thanks to Nicole Afton for facilitating a thought-provoking session on leading organizations through change initiatives!",
    "date": "2023-10-16",
    "content": "<p>Many thanks to Nicole Afton for facilitating a thought-provoking session on leading organizations through change initiatives! It was great exchanging perspectives with her, Rod Lacey, and Matt Johnson.</p>\n<p>Some key takeaways for executives leading their organizations through periods of rapid change:</p>\n<p>üî¢ Instead of overwhelming employees with data, AI can act as a \"smart indexing tool\" to help leaders grasp what matters most.</p>\n<p>ü§ù Rather than automating tasks people enjoy, AI should complement human skills and energies. The goal is to lift burdens, not compete.</p>\n<p>‚è±Ô∏è Organizations shouldn't wait for the mythical \"perfect moment\" to understand employee motivations. Assess constantly with confidential pulse surveys.</p>\n<p>üó∫Ô∏è To drive rapid change, identify \"pioneers\" who get a thrill from trailblazing vs trying to convince the skeptics.</p>\n<p>‚úçÔ∏è Leaders shouldn't just communicate the \"what\", but the \"why\" of change repeatedly. Help employees write their own chapter in the story.</p>\n<p>I hope viewers left feeling optimistic about leading change when combining emerging technologies like AI with human-centric leadership.</p>\n<p>Kudos again to Nicole for assembling a diverse panel to explore this complex topic.</p>\n<p>Please reach out if you would like to continue the discussion!</p>\n",
