    "id": "post-2023-10-06-7116053640783482880",
    "title": "Feel free to ask me clarifying questions until you have enough information to proceed.",
    "date": "2023-10-06",
    "content": "<p>Feel free to ask me clarifying questions until you have enough information to proceed.</p>\n<p>AI pro tip: append this to your prompts for higher-quality results.</p>\n<p>Everyone is excited about forthcoming \"agentic\" AI capabilities, whereby <a href=\"https://chat.openai.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ChatGPT</a> et al will proactively retrieve and transform information on your behalf before producing an answer (√† la Code Interpreter/Advanced Data Analysis or the recently revived Web Browsing); however...</p>\n<p>Retrieval Augmented Generation works regardless of whether it‚Äôs the computer or the user who‚Äôs actually retrieving the information.</p>\n<p>In my experience, it‚Äôs generally easier for the human to do it (especially if it's coming from your private repository), and probably will be for the foreseeable future.</p>\n<p>About a year ago, it occurred to me that \"the search engines of the future would ask YOU questions,\" and it's turned out to be the case with <a href=\"https://chat.openai.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ChatGPT</a> (and <a href=\"https://claude.ai\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claude</a>) that as soon as you invite AI to become your curious thought partner‚Äînot just your eager first-year analyst to whom you delegate rote tasks‚Äîthat's when things start getting REALLY interesting.</p>\n",
