    "id": "post-2023-07-11-7084574947582304259",
    "title": "Is there room for a new ‚ÄùI‚Äù in the trust equation?",
    "date": "2023-07-11",
    "content": "<p>Is there room for a new ‚ÄùI‚Äù in the trust equation?</p>\n<p>Here's why we shouldn't JUST focus on Intimacy; \"Interestingness\" can help build trust, too. Let's discover how pursuing unique interests can amplify your trustworthiness.</p>\n<p>The trust equation: Trust = (Credibility + Reliability + Intimacy) / Self-Orientation is a widely accepted concept, especially in the professional sphere. But what if we replaced \"Intimacy\" with \"Interestingness\"?</p>\n<p>While \"Intimacy\" can feel nebulous in a business context, \"Interestingness\"‚Äîdefined as nurturing a unique, reality-anchored perspective‚Äîis something even people who aren't \"people people\" can actively cultivate.</p>\n<p>It's tempting to mistakenly equate being \"interesting\" with adopting a contrarian stance, but I propose a different approach. Cultivating interestingness involves self-discovery, understanding our intrinsic motivations, and using them to traverse unexplored territory on the frontier of human knowledge and experience.</p>\n<p>There, we may unearth pockets of insight where conventional heuristics fail, offering unique perspectives that others value. Ultimately, adopting a contrarian stance would only be an accidental consequence of making a tremendous discovery.</p>\n<p>This journey makes us not just interesting but also trustworthy. Our unique insights become valuable, we become more credible, and our intrinsic motivation creates an authenticity that enhances intimacy.</p>\n<p>To become more trustworthy, ask yourself, ‚ÄúWhat totally fascinates me?‚Äù and pursue it. Discover and seek to answer questions no one has ever asked; keep moving forward, relentlessly.</p>\n<p>I suspect that \"Interestingness\" might correlate with lower self-orientation. Someone with the freedom and the intrinsic motivation to venture along their unique path is less likely to be primarily driven by mimetic competition for limited resources like money or status; they are led instead by curiosity.</p>\n<p>In conclusion, supplementing \"Intimacy\" with \"Interestingness\" in the trust equation is an actionable idea that can help you become more trustworthy: Investing some of your invaluable attention each week (√† la Google's 20% time) into hyper-individuated exploration, experimentation, and discovery for its own sake.</p>\n<p>What do you think? Does \"Interestingness\" have a place in the trust equation? Let‚Äôs start a conversation.</p>\n<p>#TrustEquation #Interestingness #ProfessionalDevelopment</p>\n",
    "excerpt": "Is there room for a new ‚ÄùI‚Äù in the trust equation? Here's why we shouldn't JUST focus on Intimacy; \"Interestingness\" can help build trust, too. Let's discover...",
