    "id": "post-2023-04-14-7052678733299638273",
    "title": "‚ÄúIt may drive us insane.‚Äù",
    "date": "2023-04-14",
    "content": "<p>‚ÄúIt may drive us insane.‚Äù</p>\n<p>I strongly agree with Lanier‚Äôs sentiment in this piece.</p>\n<p>The ‚ÄúAI will kill us all via nano-bots and viruses‚Äù doomsday cult proclamations are IMO unhelpful and a distraction from the very real danger that in affording each one of us the ability to disintermediate experts and institutions and index the sum of human knowledge as we please, we may become unintelligible to each other and lose our grips on reality.</p>\n<p>This is the dark side of hyper-individuation, whereby everyone will increasingly have an opportunity to celebrate their differences and find meaningful work in line with their intrinsic motivations and strengths.</p>\n<p>If we forget that the digital world is a reflection of the real world (the map is not the territory, etc), then we run the risk of falling into insanity-inducing information loops.</p>\n<p>This is already happening (eg online radicalization, video game addiction, social media psychosis ‚Äî all of was brought to my and Beko Jang‚Äôs attention as we developed the curriculum for Virgils Inc); it will become more of a cause for concern as AR/VR, crypto, and AI intersect and digital experiences become increasingly immersive, financialized, and personalized.</p>\n<p>Something for knowledge workers, employers, parents, and policymakers to ponder, especially as that calls for regulation grow louder.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://lnkd.in/eb_Yg7GV\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">https://lnkd.in/eb_Yg7GV</a></p>\n<p>#artificialintelligence</p>\n",
