    "id": "post-2022-12-27-7013523797706186752",
    "title": "There is a lot of (well founded) concern amongst teachers about the problems AI poses to the educational process and broader system, e.",
    "date": "2022-12-27",
    "content": "<p>There is a lot of (well founded) concern amongst teachers about the problems AI poses to the educational process and broader system, e.g., GPT-3‚Äìgenerated book reports.</p>\n<p>Instead of working against AI, I would recommend educators to consider fundamentally rethinking workflow and process when it comes to their work with students (and, by extension, any kind of creative information or knowledge-based output).</p>\n<p>AI actually ENHANCES creativity by augmenting divergent thinking and making convergent thinking more efficient (see attached image).</p>\n<p>This is a good thing: the public education system has traditionally had an emphasis on control and standardization, and AI allows for more individual differentiation, thereby increasing the range of ideas available for students to explore and inviting them to develop novel syntheses that can be critiqued and refined in social settings.</p>\n<p>AI can help teachers in this regard by allowing them to:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Change the nature of the assignments that they do,</li>\n<li>Encouraging students to use artificial intelligence, and</li>\n<li>Reconfiguring the rubrics by which they grade assignments or essays to be optimized for creativity, utility, and quality.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>For example, instead of just expecting students to write a book report about a particular book, teachers can raise the bar and have students come up with some kind of original thought or intertextual reading between that book and something else in which they're deeply interested. Students might use a discursive AI agent to explore ideas or topics contained within the text that interest them, and the AI might even pose critical thinking questions to them‚Äîall the while their discourse is recorded and trascribed, raw material for original writing.</p>\n<p>With AI assistance, the quality of the work that students can do in the same amount of time should be significantly higher.</p>\n<p>On the teacher side, AI can help by looking at the corpus of submitted essays or assignments and surfacing the most compelling, unique, and interesting insights for an emotionally charged group discussion during class.</p>\n<p>Submission would be judged not on their merits as summaries of the original text, but at a much higher level: on their originality and creative interpretation.</p>\n<p>Teachers can also use the extra time freed up by machine assistance to do relational work with the students who would really benefit from a 1:1 intervention: e.g., to tease out their motivations, provide encouragement, and remove limits to creative potential.</p>\n<p>With AI assistance, teachers and students can spend more time doing things that are MORE HUMAN, create higher quality work more efficiently, make better use of common classroom time, and accelerate subject mastery.</p>\n<p>#artificialintelligence #education #creativity</p>\n",
    "excerpt": "There is a lot of (well founded) concern amongst teachers about the problems AI poses to the educational process and broader system, e.g., GPT-3‚Äìgenerated book...",
