    "id": "post-2022-12-10-7007393534735470592",
    "title": "Are you a Chief-of-Staff struggling to get your team in sync and hyper-focused?",
    "date": "2022-12-10",
    "content": "<p>Are you a Chief-of-Staff struggling to get your team in sync and hyper-focused?</p>\n<p>You might have something to learn from this one 2,300-year-old Greek guy...</p>\n<p>When it comes to company success, there are many factors at play, such as strong leadership, a clear vision, and a solid business model. But if you want to dig deeper and understand the underlying mechanisms that drive your organization's success, you may want to look at Aristotle's \"four causes.</p>\n<p>Aristotle's four causes are a concept from ancient Greek philosophy that can be applied to various fields, including corporate strategy and management.</p>\n<p>The four causes are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The final cause (the purpose or end that something serves),</li>\n<li>The formal cause (the shape or form that something takes),</li>\n<li>The material cause (the physical substance out of which something is made), and</li>\n<li>The efficient cause (the agent or force that brings something into being).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In the context of company strategy, the final cause is the ultimate goal that the company is striving to achieve. There are multiple \"final causes\" at any given time: long-term vision and infinite mission, a proximal quarterly objective, and the priority atop your daily task list.</p>\n<p>To maximize team cohesion and coordinated action, all of these should be chained together.</p>\n<p>The formal cause is also important in corporate strategy. This is the shape or form that the company's strategy takes. It is both explicit (e.g., management processes, stated values) and implicit (e.g., unspoken cultural norms).</p>\n<p>In particular, the process of setting, syncing, and reflecting upon quarterly objectives (OKRs) is a key aspect of the formal cause. By establishing clear and measurable goals, and regularly reviewing and adjusting them, companies can ensure that their strategy is well-defined and focused on achieving their final cause, thereby cohering the final with the formal.</p>\n<p>The material and efficient causes also play important roles.</p>\n<p>The material cause refers to the resources and assets that a company uses to achieve its goals. This includes financial capital, human talent, proprietary technology, and access to insular networks.</p>\n<p>The efficient cause is the agent or force that brings the company's strategy into being. This is where human attention comes into play. In the age of digital distraction, companies need to create conditions that allow knowledge workers maximize their individual attention, align their daily activities with sources of intrinsic motivation, and direct that catalyzed attention towards a shared final cause (i.e., a mission-aligned quarterly objective).</p>\n<p>In conclusion, Chiefs-of-Staff can think about supporting their principals in the context of Aristotle's four causes: articulating a final cause, catalyzing efficient causes, implementing formal causes, and maximizing material causes.</p>\n<p>How can you apply Aristotle's 4 causes in your own work?</p>\n<p>Let me know in the comments!</p>\n<p>#chiefofstaff #startup #strategy #management #philosophy #okr</p>\n",
