    "id": "post-2022-11-28-7003014634769108992",
    "title": "When it comes to OKRs, I‚Äôm generally a stickler for the rules.",
    "date": "2022-11-28",
    "content": "<p>When it comes to OKRs, I‚Äôm generally a stickler for the rules.</p>\n<p>But there‚Äôs one rule that I often break (and often recommend clients do the same)‚Ä¶</p>\n<p>It‚Äôs that key results should be independent and uncorrelated.</p>\n<p>Now, at first glance, this rule makes a ton of sense. Ideally you only have 1x objective and 3x key results for your whole company (yes, even if you have 100+ employees), which means that you need to be extremely information-efficient with your key results.</p>\n<p>Here‚Äôs an example scenario (based on a VC-backed MedTech sales team I worked with): The team has identified an untapped segment (mid-market community health centers that generate a certain range of volume for a certain procedure every year) that they need to focus all of their energy on serving extremely well to create a market wedge and generate outsized leverage for the year ahead.</p>\n<p>Of course, the ultimate outcome the team wants to achieve is $ in revenue, BUT because the sales cycles can take longer than a quarter, they needed to figure out how to measure proxy outcomes toward that longer-term end that they could meaningfully effect in 3 months.</p>\n<p>These were:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>demos given</li>\n<li>first contacts with new prospects</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now, these two results are highly correlated, so with a ‚Äútraditional‚Äù approach to OKRs you should only pick 1. However, because ‚Äúdemos given‚Äù is a lagging indicator (and it was a new segment), we decided to include ‚Äúfirst contacts‚Äù as well. (There was a third result that measured the team‚Äôs ability to find one ‚Äúsuper fan‚Äù customer, too.)</p>\n<p>And it worked fantastically. The team knocked it out of the park and dominated the new market segment.</p>\n<p>Why?</p>\n<p>Because the two results, while correlated in ‚Äúinformation space,‚Äù were not correlated in time.</p>\n<p>It‚Äôs what I refer to as a ‚Äúvital outcome‚Äù and ‚Äúquality input‚Äù KR combo.</p>\n<p>At the first few weekly syncs, there wasn‚Äôt enough new information in re ‚Äúdemos given‚Äù to confidently make tactical changes, so the team instead focused on pulling the levers for ‚Äúfirst contact,‚Äù which led to the lagging outcomes and generated insights, used to affect ALL outcomes.</p>\n<p>This intense focus on reliably achieving a proximal outcome (really a quality input toward the vital, longer-term outcome) created momentum that led the team to achieve something they didn‚Äôt know was possible in such a short period of time.</p>\n<p>So, next time you‚Äôre setting OKRs‚Äîespecially on the ‚Äúfrontier‚Äù‚Äîconsider breaking the ‚Äúindependent KR‚Äù rule by pairing a quality leading indicator with a vital lagging indicator, thereby allowing your team to strike a balance between high-agency action and long-term thinking that helps them do incredible things.</p>\n<p>#okrs #management #strategy</p>\n",
