    "id": "post-2022-11-18-6999395643433611265",
    "title": "When you‚Äôre managing a remote team, high-quality one-on-ones are critical.",
    "date": "2022-11-18",
    "content": "<p>When you‚Äôre managing a remote team, high-quality one-on-ones are critical.</p>\n<p>When done well, they complement your weekly cross-functional team meetings. You don‚Äôt have over-engineer them, but a little structure will go a long way.</p>\n<p>Here‚Äôs a simple approach you can use to make the most of that time and keep your team on track:</p>\n<p>First, schedule a recurring weekly 60‚Äì90-minute block with each of your direct reports (yes, I know this seems like a huge amount of time, but in order to surface valuable information, you‚Äôll need to create sufficient space for insights to surface ‚Ä¶ 30 minutes is simply not enough to engage in the kind of discourse that unearths root causes ‚Ä¶ this pays off tremendously in the long run). I recommend doing it in the afternoon (1-4pm) so you can protect everyone‚Äôs high-quality attention in the morning, which can be invested into deep work.</p>\n<p>If you have four directs, that means that 2-3:30pm M-Th let‚Äôs say is budgeted for 1:1s.</p>\n<p>Then, create a private shared doc (I prefer a Google doc) with two sections:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>A parking lot with bulleted topics to be attended to during the 1:1. If something comes up during the week (e.g., a ‚Äúlearning moment‚Äù opportunity after a poor interaction with a prospect or team mate), simply account for it in a single bullet so you can have a live discussion during the 1:1. I recommend keeping this list short - you‚Äôll discuss 1‚Äì3 bullets during the 1:1.</li>\n<li>A table with 4 columns and three rows, where you‚Äôll reflect monthly on performance expectations and identify opportunities for improvement. In the first column, identify the areas (one per row) that the employee is responsible for (e.g. ‚Äúdemand generation‚Äù) with a short, qualitative description of what they‚Äôre expected to achieve. In the second column, you will record your perception of the employee‚Äôs performance from 1-10. In third, the employee will use the same scale to rate themselves. Update this once per month and bridge gaps through dialog: first, those between your perception and the employee‚Äôs perception until you reach a shared rating; then, those between where they are and where they need to be (9/10, let‚Äôs say). This is an opportunity to get on the same page in terms of performance and identify activities they can use to improve performance (some of which will require investment on your or the company‚Äôs part).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This approach is both effective and efficient because it frames your conversations in terms of a simple formal structure (in alignment with the company‚Äôs goals) while leaving space for rapport building and deeper conversations that surface high-quality information.</p>\n<p>One last tip: when you get the urge to make a statement or give direction, ask yourself if there‚Äôs a way to ask a question instead.</p>\n<p>What else can managers do to take 1:1s to the next level??</p>\n<p>Add your tips in the comments! üëá</p>\n",
    "excerpt": "When you‚Äôre managing a remote team, high-quality one-on-ones are critical. When done well, they complement your weekly cross-functional team meetings. You...",
